liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Middle East Correspondent Allyson Horn The UN says around 50,000 pregnant women in Gaza are not able to obtain basic healthcare for themselves or their unborn child. About 5,500 of them are expected to give birth within a month. The ABC's team in Gaza met 24 year-old Lina Raad Hammas and her two-day old newborn twins. She fled northern Gaza to the south, and is now living on the concrete floor of an educational college building that's been turned into a refuge. Her house has since been destroyed by an Israeli airstrike. "The situation is terrible,' she said. "There is no food, no electricity, no water, especially when I've just had my baby. "It is stressful. I even borrowed my mattress from the neighbours." Lina said she is yet to name her twins because she's too stressed and exhausted. She is worried her babies will die from starvation. "I just need water for my babies," she said. "I wanted to bottle feed them, but I could not clean the bottles. "I kept breast-feeding them but I don't have enough milk for both of them."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: US Secretary of State Antony Blinken and Defense Secretary Lloyd Austin say the United States expects the Israel-Gaza war to escalate through involvement by proxies of Iran. They asserted that the Biden administration is prepared to respond if American personnel or armed forces become the target of any such hostilities. "This is not what we want, not what we're looking for. We don't want escalation," Mr Blinken said. "We don't want to see our forces or our personnel come under fire. But if that happens, we're ready for it." Mr Austin, echoed the sentiment saying "what we're seeing is a prospect of a significant escalation of attacks on our troops and our people throughout the region." He said the US has the right to self-defense "and we won't hesitate to take the appropriate action." Hamas leader Ismail Haniyeh and Iranian Foreign Minister Hossein Amirabdollahian discussed the means of stopping the Israeli "brutal crimes" in the besieged Gaza enclave, the group said in a statement late Sunday. AP/Reuters

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Gaza's most crowded United Nations relief shelter is currently sheltering around 21,000 people, according to the UN's latest update. "The number of [displaced people] per shelter has reached in many shelters 4,400," the update says, adding the buildings were "designed to host 1,500-2,000". It also notes "entire neighbourhoods" have been destroyed in the Gaza Strip since October 7. "The Gaza Ministry of Public Works reported the destruction of 15,749 housing units and the rendering of 10,935 housing units uninhabitable, as of 21 October," it says. "Another 142,500 housing units sustained minor to moderate damage. " The total number of housing units destroyed or damaged accounts for at least 43 per cent of all housing units in the Gaza Strip."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Kristin Stubbins, who was acting CEO for PwC Australia after Tom Seymour stepped down in the wake of the tax leaks scandal, has announced she will leave the consultancy giant at the end of January next year. In a post on her LinkedIn this afternoon, Ms Stubbins said "the time has come to put my family first for the next few months and to recharge my batteries". Ms Stubbins was elevated to acting CEO of PwC Australia in mid-May, after Mr Seymour disclosed he was one of 12 PwC partners who were included in confidential tax information leaked by PwC's former head of international tax, Peter-John Collins. Ms Stubbins was replaced by current PwC Australia CEO Kevin Burrowes. In her LinkedIn post, Ms Stubbins said the last six months had been "very challenging". "But I am proud I had the courage to make the decisions that needed to be made including holding people accountable for their actions, protecting people who needed protection, deciding to sell the government consulting business to protect jobs and embarking on the Dr Switkowski review to help PwC Australia understand how it needs to change," she wrote. "I am confident that the new Management Leadership Team is totally committed to making these changes and that PwC Australia will go forward now with a focus on becoming the leading professional services firm in the next few years. "I have had the privilege to work with an amazing team of people to set up the transformation program and to draft the strategic plan that we will launch at the end of November." PwC Australia has been contacted for comment.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Former acting PwC Australia CEO Kristin Stubbins to leave firm in January

Ms Stubbins was elevated to acting CEO of PwC Australia in mid-May, after Mr Seymour disclosed he was one of 12 PwC partners who were included in confidential tax information leaked by PwC's former head of international tax, Peter-John Collins.
Ms Stubbins was replaced by current PwC Australia CEO Kevin Burrowes.

"I am confident that the new Management Leadership Team is totally committed to making these changes and that PwC Australia will go forward now with a focus on becoming the leading professional services firm in the next few years.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Well, the market was nothing if not consistent today — consistently bad that is. It was down around 0.8% at the open, and closed off the same amount, having traded in a pretty narrow range throughout the day. The big losers were the same by the end of the day as at the beginning — energy down 3.1%, led by coal miners, with the rest of the mining sector off an average 2.3%. The resilient sectors also remained the same: healthcare, up 1.8% and consumer non-cyclicals up 0.7%. On the ASX 200, 124 companies lost ground while only 61 finished in the black, with 15 going neither up nor down. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Medibank has become the latest company to explore a shorter working week, announcing 250 of its employees will take part in a six-month trial of a four-day work week. The private health insurer says the trial, designed with 4 Day Week Global and monitored by Macquarie University, is part of their wider commitment to be "the healthiest workplace in Australia". Workers involved in Medibank's trial will experiment with the 100:80:100 model — where employees and bosses agree to 100% of their previous pay, for 80% of the work time, while committing to 100% productivity. For full-time Medibank employees, it means they only work four days a week, while part-time employees are pro-rated. "There are lots of pressures out there right now, whether it's cost of living or people managing their work and home commitments," Medibank's Kylie Bishop said. "We're constantly thinking about how we can help balance that for our people and invest in their health and wellbeing to help prevent issues like burnout." Medibank's four-day week trial comes as Unilever, which makes consumer goods like Rexona, Streets and Dove, is about to wind down its year-long trial next month that around 500 employees took part in. Curious about the four-day work week? You can read more about it (and the push to expand it) below:
